        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Fortis viri indigna, et sanè ignaua mors: nobilis Anima, cariori precio erat Vendenda, non gratìs
                    abijcienda. Inuictus Animus, heroica[m]</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>vindictam spirans, multô potiùs, in confertissimos hostes furiosè inuolasset, et
                    salte[m] honorata[m] morte[m] viuidè, pra[e]ualideq[ue] extorsisset. Absit, vt hîc, Exitus acta probet: cu[m]
                    effo[e]minata ista mors, mascula[e]</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref book_title="Heroides" language="LA" person="Ovid" text="Exitus acta probet"/>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>strenua[e]q[ue] excellentis</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Ducis Vita[e], condonanda Videat[u]r.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>An unworthy and truly ignoble death of a courageous man: a noble mindset was to be sold for a steep price and not to be thrown away freely. The invincible mindset, breathing heroical vengeance, much rather would rush furiously
             against enemy troops and at least take away by force a honorable death lively and very strongly. God forbid that here "the end justifies the means": since that womanish death may seem to give up the masculine and vigorous excellent life of the general.</translation> 
            <!--JG: Unsure about part starting from 'absit'. Why use of gen.? Chris, please check-->
            <!-- CG: My attempt: "God forbid, as here, that his death represent his deeds, since it seems that the effeminate death of the masculine and vigorous life of an excellent leader must be forgiven." -->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="drawe their swordes" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Ferro aperit[u]r via.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The road is revealed by the sword.</translation> <!--JG: Seems like Harvey quoted this, perhaps from Virgil? Can't find anything though-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>In extremo actu deficere, turpe. Aut viuendu[m], aut moriendum magnificè.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>It is shameful to disappoint in the final deed. One must either live or die magnificently.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
